soxfox: calris, yeah, my goal with it was to reduce latency, matching IRC and other chat systems where the server tells the client a new message is available
soxfox: it also technically reduces network traffic, but not by an interesting amount
soxfox: I might see if I can make the server work without tying up the thread that got the SEND command
soxfox: i guess the other simple change would be to make it so only a 0 response ends the wait
d_m: if i were designing it i'd want to avoid a notification "interrupting" an in-progress respnose sequence
d_m: in other words you want to be sure that if the client expects a response to SEND or whatever, that you don't send a notification first by mistake
d_m: one of the nice things about the current design is that commands all originate with the client so you can avoid races
d_m: i'm not sure you can totally eliminate notification races without some kind of token, but you could make them less likely
waso amisi: what if, when a client is waiting, any command is implicitly also a STOP
waso amisi: e.g. WAIT n\nSEND foo\n would get back 0\nn\nn+1
waso amisi: and then, if there's a notification inbetween, the server just doesn't send the STOP reply
soxfox: right now I have it so that the client always sends STOP before any command and waits for the stop response
soxfox: I think that avoided notification races
soxfox: I think using every command as implicit stop wouldn't work on its own, you couldn't tell if the next response was a notification sent right before your command or a response to the command
soxfox: the trick that made STOP work without that issue was making STOP and WAIT responses equivalent
waso amisi: what if your client sends STOP, then gets a notification?
waso amisi: does it handle the trailing STOP reply?
waso amisi: that's the only race i can think of if you're always sending STOP
soxfox: right now the server can never actually send that
soxfox: that's something to worry about when I make WAIT keep running after one message
waso amisi: it could though, if a message came in between when STOP got sent and when the server processed it
waso amisi: i think if you move the reply part of STOP into the if statement it solves that
soxfox: Oh, maybe I wrote it wrong
soxfox: I think I meant to do what you said ><
waso amisi: happy to be a second set of eyes lol
soxfox: Yeah, that's just a bug on my part. STOP was only meant to reply if it actually stopped something
waso amisi: gotcha, then yeah i think that's all sound
soxfox: so the next things I'll look at are keeping the WAIT command running after it delivers responses and also adjusting the threading
soxfox: I actually misread your earlier message about implicit stop too, I think it would actually work, don't know if it's worth it though
d_m: i see. i guess if you are waiting you never expect 0 to be your first msg
d_m: so you can distinguish a STOP response from a notification
soxfox: Exactly
d_m: ok yeah, if you handle notifications in the client thread and are careful it should be ok.
d_m: one interesting side effect is that you'll end up closing some idle/poor tcp connections that aren't able to deliver notifications
d_m: whereas a client that doesn't attempt to poll can keep a "stale" connection open and then start using it later when link quality improves.
d_m: whether that's a useful property or just a weird coincidence... *shrug*
d_m: clients can always reconnect if their connection dies so in practice it's probably not a big deal
d_m: and most (all?) clients have periodic polling built in anyway
soxfox: oh, that is an interesting detail
soxfox: probably ok in practice though, and the way I have it working right now doesn't stop people from making polling clients
d_m: right.
soxfox: or non-polling ones as the case may be
waso amisi: irc's message command being PRIVMSG implies there was a MSG command before it
waso amisi: wonder if it started off as one big chatroom like this
soxfox: d_m, if I continue to improve the wait feature, would it be something you'd want to include in the actual server?
d_m: i'm not sure. it probably depends on the final implementation and also whether client authors want to support it.
d_m: in my case, i always query for messages right after SEND, so i don't really notice any polling latency with my own messages.
soxfox: makes sense
soxfox: yeah, I do the same, but I've found a couple of times (like just now), it increases the chance that I miss a newer message before I respond
d_m: right.
