snufkin: waso amisi, my aim is to make the tests as readable as possible, data locallity is important IMHO, because you can end up with hundreds of tests.
snufkin: tbsp, once the function is debugged and tested, I tend to use ut as a black box, that is why testing is important, one is responsible to end the strings with a null byte, but that is the same as any other null terminated string function. However I'll take your advise and keep the "normal" versions. 
snufkin: ;msgs/zen /test    ;msgs/assertions /set    etc. so the user can pick their style. :)
snufkin: tbsp, another option is
snufkin: { "Zen 00 } /test    { "Assertions 00 } /set ...
snufkin: Inside the functions I SWP2r STH2r then just print, however then this wouldn't work
snufkin: ;msgs/zen /test
snufkin: I think as long as the test functions is properly docubented it shouldn't be an issue.
snufkin: Do you think this approach is less confusing?
snufkin: I tend not to use this because it also assembles raw  [ JSI length* ] for every string, however tests are not "release" so it doesnt matter that much? I could also use the lencht to print them as counted strings (not needing the null terminator) 
snufkin: { "Assertions } /test
snufkin: visually the syntax is already simpler because of the null, less error prone (having to test the tests themselves is not how it should mork
snufkin: *work
snufkin: Thanks for the feedback :)
snufkin: I did a string interpolation routine, I'll leave it here in case you fund it handy :)
