sporeball: what are some high level tasks the return stack is used for in real world Uxntal code?
sporeball: i drew a bath today & thought of strange fork idea that might increase word size at the cost of the R mode
sporeball: not sure how unsound it would be, because i haven't written 3 million lines of Uxntal yet...
sporeball: so the only place i've ever used the R mode is of course in JMP2r
chloe: the return stack is often used for juggling around numbers in large complicated loops
chloe: https://git.sr.ht/~angelwood/eclipse/tree/main/item/eclipse.tal#L147
chloe: this is some of my code for example
chloe: there is two loops &>i and &>j
chloe: and the stack gets too cluddered if i dont move some of them over into the return stack
sporeball: chloe, did you find this was impossible to do without the return stack?
sporeball: or just tricky
waso amisi: in theory you can juggle a max of 6 bytes on either stack without storing stuff to memory
waso amisi: but it gets really ugly
waso amisi: e.g. moving byte 6 to the top is ROT2k NIP2 NIP2 POP
chloe: sporeball, the deeper you need to go into the stack the trickier it gets
chloe: in the worst case you need to store variables in ram and load them back in later
chloe: but its best to avoid doing so as the stack is always faster then ram
sporeball nods
waso amisi: https://paste.amehut.dev/~aleteoryx/17e274faf0bd8ee931feb72f4fc0a4cbf75e8b0f
waso amisi: just a memcpy gets pretty hairy with no return stack
tbsp: you can juggle values in doors using STR as well
tbsp: I feel like you could give up return mode and lean heavier on doors...
tbsp: of course you'd still need a RET (JMP2r) somehow
tbsp: I'd be curious to see an attempt of a no-return-mode uxn variant that also didn't allow SMC
tbsp: aka, "how awkward can we make uxntal for imaginary gains?" :P
